{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1ae0cbbe-d214-4fb9-8656-0c5c5a8c5f97","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` fires on **iOS/macOS** only (when the app enters the background) and provides a `BackgroundingEventArgs` you can use to save state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d7676952-4350-4253-a7f2-5c33e3e39d7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"F3C5:2EB5E6:1F713C2:233E9BD:69E819FE"},"id":"07efcd68-e2fc-4710-a015-ccc8802397fa","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:44:54.798Z","parentId":"d0a78863-95cc-4b26-aa13-974a832bcd08"}
